      Tesla
   =20
 =20
Tesla Inc. is an electric car company, but arguably its most important miss=
ion is generating cash for Elon Musk. This is not just me saying that. In 2=
017, Musk=C2=A0told a Tesla director that he needed billions of dollars=C2=
=A0from Tesla =E2=80=9Cso that I can put as much as possible towards minimi=
zing existential risk by putting the money towards Mars.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
Colonizing Mars is an expensive endeavor,=E2=80=9D a Delaware Chancery Cour=
t judge wrote this year.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CMusk believes he has a moral obligat=
ion to direct his wealth toward that goal,=C2=A0and Musk views his compensa=
tion from Tesla as a means of bankrolling that mission.=E2=80=9D Maybe Mars=
 was more of a 2017 thing, and in 2024 Musk has competing priorities (artif=
icial intelligence, brain implants, Twitter), but the point is:=09Elon Musk=
 has big plans for the world, and a sense of moral mission in pursuing them=
.=09Those plans require a lot of capital.=09Except Tesla (now), which is a =
public company with about $500 billion worth of liquid public stock, and wh=
ich he can use for the other stuff.I do not want to suggest that Tesla is p=
urely Elon Musk=E2=80=99s personal piggybank, because that=E2=80=99s not tr=
ue. It makes electric cars.=C2=A0It continues to invest in new projects. It=
 has, historically, generated a whole lot of value for Tesla shareholders=
=C2=A0other=C2=A0than Elon Musk, though not as much recently. (It has lost =
more than 60% of its value since the peak in 2021.) But Telsa is=C2=A0also=
=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s main piggybank, and he has a lot of needs. Musk went a=
nd solved the (difficult, capital-intensive) problem of electric cars, and =
now Tesla is his main source of wealth for solving the many other difficult=
, capital-intensive problems that interest him.You know the story: In 2018,=
 to satisfy Musk=E2=80=99s Mars ambitions, Tesla=E2=80=99s board granted hi=
m a package of conditional Tesla stock options that would be worth somethin=
g like $55 billion if Tesla succeeded wildly. It did: By 2021 Tesla was wor=
th $1.2 trillion, Musk got=C2=A0all the options, and for a time they were w=
orth more than $100 billion. He used his vast Tesla wealth =E2=80=94=C2=A0s=
elling shares and borrowing against them
  [1]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to fund his various other projects, like buying Twitte=
r and also I am sure something Mars-related. By this year, he was back aski=
ng Tesla=E2=80=99s board for more money. But meanwhile a disgruntled Tesla =
shareholder named Richard Tornetta had sued the company, arguing that Musk=
=E2=80=99s pay package was illegal, and in January that Delaware judge rule=
d that it was. And so Musk=E2=80=99s options disappeared, arguably making a=
t least a theoretical dent in his ability to do Mars, AI, brains, tweets or=
 whatever it is he=E2=80=99s up to now.Today Tesla filed a proxy statement =
for its 2024 annual meeting, asking shareholders to fix that problem and tu=
rn the money faucet back on. There are two specific asks:=09That Delaware j=
udge ruled that Musk=E2=80=99s 2018=C2=A0pay package was illegal in part be=
cause she found problems with the shareholder vote approving it. So Tesla i=
s asking the shareholders to approve the 2018=C2=A0pay package again, so Mu=
sk can get his options back.=09It was a=C2=A0Delaware=C2=A0judge who ruled =
that Musk=E2=80=99s pay package was illegal, because Tesla, like most big U=
S public companies, is incorporated in Delaware. Presumably a=C2=A0Texas=C2=
=A0judge wouldn=E2=80=99t do that, since Texas apparently loves Musk as a m=
atter of state policy. So Tesla is asking the shareholders to approve reinc=
orporating the company in Texas.=C2=A0Each of these raises some complicatio=
ns.First, the economics of re-approving the 2018 pay package. In 2018, Tesl=
a=E2=80=99s board granted Musk 12 tranches of stock options, each represent=
ing 1% of Tesla=E2=80=99s stock at the time. The tranches would vest based =
on performance targets, particularly market capitalization targets: The fir=
st tranche vested if Tesla hit a $100 billion market cap (up from about $59=
 billion at the time of the grant), and the other 11 tranches would vest at=
 $50 billion increments, up to $650 billion for the final tranche.
  [2]
=C2=A0He had 10 years to hit those milestones; he hit them in three. Today=
=E2=80=99s proxy says:The Board in 2018 believed that the hurdles for perfo=
rmance were exceptionally high, and subsequently, Mr. Musk met =E2=80=94 an=
d exceeded =E2=80=94 each and every key milestone in the 2018 CEO Performan=
ce Award, milestones that have resulted in remarkable value creation for ou=
r stockholders.And it quotes shareholder letters saying things like
  [3]
:The requirements of the 2018 package were extraordinarily ambitious=E2=80=
=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89and they were delivered. It is not reasonable for inve=
stors to expect to re-absorb the canceled options and consider all that val=
ue creation to have been delivered to us for no consideration.And:My choice=
 for Tesla being my primary investment is because of the pay package select=
ed for Elon Musk. No different tha[n] many sales personnel, when you perfor=
m, you are awarded, sometimes very handsomely for it. To the opposite of th=
is, many CEO=E2=80=99s are awarded great sums even when the company i[n] ma=
ny cases, drastically fails to perform for its shareholders which is why I =
looked at them=C2=A0years ago and didn=E2=80=99t choose them.And, right, by=
 2021, all the milestones had been achieved. But Tesla=E2=80=99s market cap=
italization, as of yesterday=E2=80=99s close, was just a hair over $500 bil=
lion; it was lower this morning. Four of the milestones =E2=80=94=C2=A0cove=
ring roughly one-third of Musk=E2=80=99s options =E2=80=94=C2=A0have been u=
n-achieved! Of course in 2018, shareholders could reasonably have said =E2=
=80=9Cif he gets this company to $650 billion, that will be amazing, and we=
 should reward him,=E2=80=9D and if later the market cap fell they=E2=80=99=
d have no argument for taking the rewards back. But they=E2=80=99re being a=
sked to re-approve the grants in 2024, and =E2=80=9Cwe need to reward Musk =
for making this a $650 billion company=E2=80=9D is a bit of an odder ask wh=
en it=E2=80=99s actually a $500 billion company.Second, the law of re-appro=
ving the pay package. It=E2=80=99s actually not obvious that this would=C2=
=A0work. Here is roughly=C2=A0how Delaware executive pay law works
  [4]
:=09In general, a company=E2=80=99s board of directors can pay its chief ex=
ecutive officer whatever they think is fair, and a court won=E2=80=99t seco=
nd-guess them.=09Unless=C2=A0the CEO is also a =E2=80=9Ccontrolling shareho=
lder,=E2=80=9D as Musk is,
  [5]
=C2=A0in which case a court will review the pay package for =E2=80=9Centire=
 fairness.=E2=80=9D=09If the shareholders, in a fully informed vote, approv=
e the pay package, then the burden of proving that it is entirely fair=C2=
=A0falls on people who object to it.=09If they don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0or if the vote isn=E2=80=99t fully informed =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the burd=
en of proving entire fairness falls on Musk and the directors.In January, t=
he judge found that the shareholders had voted to approve the 2017 pay pack=
age, but that their vote was not fully informed, because they did not know =
about some of the conflicts of interest that the board had in creating the =
package. So the burden of proving it was fair fell on Tesla, and the judge =
concluded that it wasn=E2=80=99t, writing that it was =E2=80=9Can unfathoma=
ble sum=E2=80=9D and suggesting that the board could reasonably have accomp=
lished its goals while paying Musk less.Now the shareholders will vote agai=
n. Let=E2=80=99s assume that their vote this time will be fully informed. (=
They can read the judge=E2=80=99s opinion! It=E2=80=99s attached to the pro=
xy statement!) But then Tornetta could sue again, arguing that the pay pack=
age still isn=E2=80=99t fair. This time, the burden of proof will be on him=
. But =E2=80=A6=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t he prove his case by attaching the judge=
=E2=80=99s previous opinion finding that the pay package wasn=E2=80=99t fai=
r? If the pay package wasn=E2=80=99t fair in January, then arguably it isn=
=E2=80=99t fair now, and shareholder approval might not fix that.Now, I=E2=
=80=99m not sure that=E2=80=99s right.
  [6]
 But I=E2=80=99m not sure it=E2=80=99s wrong, and neither is Tesla. The pro=
xy statement says:The Company is asking its stockholders to ratify the 2018=
 CEO Performance Award under Delaware common and statutory law. Delaware co=
mmon law ratification permits a Delaware corporation to validate a corporat=
e act where the actors that purported to effect it lacked requisite corpora=
te authority to do so. Common law ratification can also extinguish claims f=
or breach of fiduciary duty by authorizing an act that otherwise would cons=
titute a breach. When properly implemented, common law ratification =E2=80=
=9Creaches back=E2=80=9D to validate the challenged act as of its initial e=
nactment. The Company believes that, under the Tornetta Opinion, the 2018 C=
EO Performance Award is such an act that may be ratified under Delaware com=
mon law. ...While the Company believes that the Ratification should be uphe=
ld by a Delaware court, the Special Committee noted that even a favorable v=
ote by our stockholders to ratify the 2018 CEO Performance Award may not fu=
lly resolve the matter. The Special Committee and its advisors noted that t=
hey could not predict with certainty how a stockholder vote to ratify the 2=
018 CEO Performance Award would be treated under Delaware law in these nove=
l circumstances.As I previously wrote: =E2=80=9CIt is possible that the rul=
e of this case is that Tesla is not allowed to pay Musk $55.8 billion, no m=
atter what its shareholders think, no matter how many of them vote to appro=
ve it in a fully informed vote. It=E2=80=99s enough to make you want to mov=
e to Texas.=E2=80=9DThird: Texas. I have written before about the problem w=
ith moving to Texas, which is that,=C2=A0if Tesla moves to Texas=C2=A0just=
=C2=A0to be able to pay Musk more, then some shareholder will sue in=C2=A0D=
elaware=C2=A0to=C2=A0stop=C2=A0it from moving, and a Delaware court might b=
e sympathetic. I wrote:So shareholders will go to the Delaware judge saying=
 =E2=80=9CElon Musk tried to pay himself $55 billion, and you stopped him f=
rom doing that because it was unfair to shareholders, and now he is trying =
to move Tesla to Texas so that he can (1) get rid of you and (2) pay himsel=
f $75 billion, so you have to stop him again.=E2=80=9D And I think that is =
an argument that the Delaware judge might find compelling? I mean, she did =
stop Musk from paying himself $55 billion. Presumably this move will be eve=
n more offensive.Since then, there was a February Delaware Chancery Court d=
ecision finding that TripAdvisor Inc.=E2=80=99s planned move from Delaware =
to Nevada might in fact be unfair to shareholders, and so was subject to co=
urt review, but refusing to=C2=A0stop=C2=A0the company from moving: If it t=
urns out to be unfair to shareholders, the judge reasoned, then the shareho=
lders can sue (in Delaware) for damages, but that=E2=80=99s not enough reas=
on to stop the company from moving. So it now seems unlikely that a court w=
ould stop Tesla from moving. Still, probably lawsuits.I also wrote:I am sur=
e that, when Tesla actually asks its shareholders to approve reincorporatin=
g in Texas, it will have good lawyers write a proxy statement emphasizing t=
he many corporate benefits of Texas, the importance of attracting and retai=
ning talent and the value that Musk provides to Tesla.=C2=A0And today=E2=80=
=99s proxy statement goes out of its way to say, no, we=E2=80=99re=C2=A0not=
=C2=A0just moving to Texas so we can pay Musk more, what ever gave you that=
 idea. =E2=80=9CTexas is Tesla=E2=80=99s Home,=E2=80=9D board chairperson R=
obyn Denholm writes in her letter to shareholders:=C2=A0Texas is already ou=
r business home, and we are committed to it. Gigafactory Texas is one of th=
e largest factories in the United=C2=A0States, covering 2,500 acres along t=
he Colorado River. The Gigafactory is the manufacturing hub for our most in=
novative vehicles, including the Cybertruck and the Model Y. We have a sign=
ificant number of manufacturing, operations, and engineering employees in T=
exas, and our executives are based there. Texas is where we should continue=
 working towards our mission of accelerating the world=E2=80=99s transition=
 to sustainable energy, as we lay the foundation for our growth with our ra=
mp and build of factories for our future vehicles and to help meet the dema=
nd for energy storage as well as with our progress in artificial intelligen=
ce via full self-driving and Optimus.We have received letters from thousand=
s of Tesla stockholders=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89large and small=E2=80=89=
=E2=80=94=E2=80=89supporting a move home to Texas. We have heard you, and n=
ow we formally ask that you speak in a meaningful way: and vote in favor of=
 taking Tesla to our business home of Texas.And, while the letter goes on t=
o complain about the Delaware court decision, the proxy statement elsewhere=
 suggests that the result might not have been different in Texas
  [7]
:In most areas the [Tesla Special] Committee examined, Texas and Delaware l=
aw apply essentially the same substantive rule, though Texas sometimes arti=
culates it a bit differently. These include fiduciary duties owed to the co=
rporation and the stockholders collectively, the corporate opportunities do=
ctrine, director exculpation, indemnification, advancement, the business ju=
dgment rule, and the entire fairness standard of judicial review.That is: T=
exas law is roughly the same as Delaware law, so it can=E2=80=99t be the ca=
