  [1] That is: Musk has  sold Tesla stock to raise money. He has pledged 23=
8 million shares =E2=80=94 worth about $37 billion at today=E2=80=99s price=
s =E2=80=94 to secure personal debt. Also, though, when he bought Twitter I=
nc., Twitter  borrowed about $13 billion from investment banks to pay some =
of the purchase price. That money was not secured by Tesla shares; it was n=
ot even personally guaranteed by Elon Musk. And yet it seems clear that tho=
se banks were jazzed to lend money to Twitter at now-catastrophic-looking t=
erms because they had some thought process like =E2=80=9CElon Musk is super=
-rich and will own Twitter, so this should all work out for us.=E2=80=9D Wh=
ich is, I think, ultimately a function of his big Tesla stake.


  [2] There were also operational milestones, which Tesla hit; I assume tha=
t the market cap ones are binding. This is all described on pages 64 to 73 =
of today=E2=80=99s proxy statement.


  [3] The first quote here is from a letter from T. Rowe Price to Tesla=E2=
=80=99s board, the second is from a letter to the Delaware court from a ret=
ail shareholder named Russell McClelland.


  [4] The first three pages of the January court decision give an overview =
of the rules.


  [5] You might disagree, but as a legal matter this seems pretty settled. =
Musk currently owns 20.5% of the stock, but the judge found in January that=
 he is a controlling shareholder through his share ownership, =E2=80=9Csupe=
rstar CEO=E2=80=9D status and dominance of the board. Or technically she fo=
und that he was a controlling shareholder in 2017, but I think the analysis=
 is pretty much the same today.


  [6] The judge, carefully, wrote that Tesla "failed to prove that the Gran=
t was the product of fair dealing or at a fair price," not that it *was* un=
fair; there is room for the outcome to change if the burden of proof does.


  [7] There are other interesting discussions of the differences between Te=
xas and Delaware. I have=20
mentioned the standard view that Delaware has more predictable business law=
, but the proxy argues otherwise: =E2=80=9CThe Special Committee and the Bo=
ard considered the likely relative predictability of Delaware and Texas law=
 based on differences in their judicial systems. Delaware has the most resp=
ected corporate judicial system in the country and has an extensive body of=
 corporate case law. In contrast, Texas is in the process of forming a spec=
ialized business court system (which is set to open in September 2024) and =
has a smaller body of corporate case law. This factor did not alter the bal=
ance in the Special Committee=E2=80=99s evaluation of Delaware and Texas. I=
n making this determination, the Special Committee and the Board were persu=
aded by the broadly held academic view=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89echoed by =
at least three former Delaware Supreme Court Justices and one former Chance=
llor on the Delaware Court of Chancery=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89that Delaw=
are law can be indeterminate because of its use of broad, flexible standard=
s that are applied to individual cases in a highly fact-specific way. As de=
scribed in the Special Committee Report, scholarship demonstrates a high le=
vel of reversal rate for decisions of the Delaware Court of Chancery. This =
focus on precise facts and circumstances means Delaware decisions may be le=
ss predictable for an innovative company like Tesla. Although Texas has les=
s corporate case law, as the Special Committee=E2=80=99s corporate law and =
governance expert pointed out, Texas =E2=80=98has a more code-based corpora=
te governance regime,=E2=80=99 and so does not depend on cases to set out t=
he law as much as Delaware.=E2=80=9D


  [8] This one is controversial, and some people will advise you never to d=
o this: By getting an offer elsewhere, and then taking it back to your curr=
ent employer, you have demonstrated disloyalty and lost their trust, things=
 will never be the same, and you=E2=80=99re better off starting fresh elsew=
here. Obviously this will depend on your particular circumstances but, come=
 on, in investment banking? How much loyalty do they expect?


  [9] This one is also debatable: It=E2=80=99s risky to tell your employer =
that you are leaving, and you might want to have a buttoned-up deal before =
telling them, to avoid the risk of them somehow sabotaging it? Also your of=
fer from the new bank might be very time-limited, and you might have to sig=
n before you can even try to negotiate a better deal.


  [10] I mean, depends how you count. The SEC=E2=80=99s phone crackdown dat=
es from its 2022 fiscal year; that year, it extracted $4.2 billion in total=
 penalties, of which $1.2 billion were for phones. In fiscal 2023, it extra=
cted $1.6 billion in penalties, of which about $400 million were for phones=
. So roughly a quarter of all SEC fines these days are for cell phones. I d=
on=E2=80=99t think there=E2=80=99s a bigger single category, though I could=
 be wrong.


